          <msContents>
            <summary> A collection of receipts in Latin, with two in German, of remedies chiefly for the Morbus Gallicus. On the fourth leaf is a pen-drawing of a 'Lanbicum' (alembic). The first receipt is headed 'Magister Jonathinus Rome hec dedit' and describes the making of an ointment and powder for ulcers caused by the Morbus Gallicus. The second headed 'Informatio Domini Mariani qui fecit pulverem sepissime', is for the making of another powder for the same disease. The german receipt is for the 'Sucht-Flusz'. The last receipt is 'Ad virile membrum pulvis quando primum sentitur sanies seu pustula.</summary>
            <textLang mainLang="" source="IANA">Latin</textLang>
            <msItem n="1" xml:id="MS_262_1">
              <author/>
              <title type="original">Ertzneisückhe</title>
              <title type="standard"/>
              <textLang mainLang="" source="IANA">Latin</textLang>
              <textLang mainLang="" source="IANA">German</textLang>
              <filiation>The Marianus of the second receipt is probably Franciscus Marianus, who died in 1528 and practised at Padua; he wrote a treatise on 'Morbus Gallicus'.</filiation>
              <filiation/>
            </msItem>
          </msContents>
